TEM (Fig. 1
                        ) was used to examine the morphology and size of the NGQDs. The TEM image showed the well dispersion of NGQDs with homogeneous sizes at about 2 nm (see inset of Fig. 1). Fig. 2
                         displayed the TEM, HRTEM images and XRD pattern of the Au NPs-NGQDs, respectively. It can be seen from the TEM image (inset in Fig. 2A and B), due to the immobilization of Au nanoparticles on the surface of NGQDs, the size of the nanocomposites grew to 4 nm, and the prepared nanocomposites showed good dispersion with uniform sizes. Moreover, the HRTEM image (inset in Fig. 2C) of Au NPs-NGQDs exhibited an interplanar spacing of 0.22 nm, which is corresponding to a typical single-crystal structure of the NGQDs [29]. The HRTEM image also showed an interplanar spacing of 0.235 nm of the single-crystal structure of Au NPs, which agrees with the value reported from Ref. [30]. The morphology and size characterizations certainly indicated the successful incorporation of Au nanoparticles with NGQDs without using any surfactant and reducing agent.

In addition, as a heterogeneous catalyst, the recycling ability of the Au NPs-NGQDs was evaluated (Fig. 8
                        ). The Au NPs-NGQDs exhibited little catalytic loss and good recycling ability. The conversion of 4-NP under visible light after consecutive nine cycles was still around 90%. The structure of the catalyst after recycling was evaluated by TEM (Fig. 9
                        ), which indicated no visible difference before and after nine recycling. It demonstrated that the Au NPs-NGQDs have good recycling ability and is an eminent catalyst for the degradation of 4-NP.
